  <title>How to Use OCR</title>

  <section id="what_is_ocr">
    <title>What OCR Is</title>
    <p>
      Many applications expose their content through the accessibility
      tree, so Orca can read them with no special help. Some do not.
      Terminal output from certain virtual-terminal toolkits, Electron
      apps, games, and applications using custom or older widget
      libraries can all be partly or entirely opaque to a screen reader.
    </p>
    <p>
      Orca's OCR (optical character recognition) feature reads such
      windows the way a sighted user would: it captures the pixels on
      screen, recognizes the text in them using the Tesseract OCR
      engine, and presents the result as a virtual buffer you can
      navigate, select from, copy to the clipboard, and click into. The
      original window does not need to expose anything to accessibility
      for OCR to work.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="installing">
    <title>Installing Tesseract</title>
    <p>
      OCR requires the <cmd>tesseract</cmd> command-line tool and at
      least one language data pack. On most distributions:
    </p>
    <list>
      <item>
        <p>Fedora, RHEL, and derivatives:
          <cmd>sudo dnf install tesseract tesseract-langpack-eng</cmd>
        </p>
      </item>
      <item>
        <p>Debian, Ubuntu, and derivatives:
          <cmd>sudo apt install tesseract-ocr tesseract-ocr-eng</cmd>
        </p>
      </item>
      <item>
        <p>Arch and derivatives:
          <cmd>sudo pacman -S tesseract tesseract-data-eng</cmd>
        </p>
      </item>
    </list>
    <p>
      Replace <cmd>eng</cmd> with the ISO 639-2 code for any other
      language you want OCR to recognize. You can install multiple
      language packs.
    </p>
    <p>
      If you press the OCR command without Tesseract installed, Orca
      will say "OCR unavailable: tesseract is not installed." No other
      Orca behavior is affected.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="basic_workflow">
    <title>Basic Workflow: Read a Window</title>
    <steps>
      <item>
        <p>Switch focus to the window you want to read.</p>
      </item>
      <item>
        <p>Press <keyseq><key>Orca Modifier</key><key>R</key></keyseq>.
          Orca says "Recognizing." while Tesseract processes the
          window's pixels.</p>
      </item>
      <item>
        <p>When recognition completes, Orca enters OCR mode and
          announces the number of recognized lines along with the first
          word ("OCR mode on. 47 lines. Welcome").</p>
      </item>
      <item>
        <p>Use the NumPad keys to navigate the recognized text — line
          by line with <key>KP 8</key> and <key>KP 2</key>, word by
          word with <key>KP 4</key> and <key>KP 6</key>, character by
          character with <key>KP 1</key> and <key>KP 3</key>. See
          <link xref="commands_ocr">OCR Commands</link> for the full
          list.</p>
      </item>
      <item>
        <p>Press <keyseq><key>Orca Modifier</key><key>R</key></keyseq>
          again to exit OCR mode.</p>
      </item>
    </steps>
  </section>

  <section id="copy_workflow">
    <title>Copying Text Out of Any Window</title>
    <p>
      Selecting text in OCR mode works the way it does in a normal text
      editor, just with NumPad keys instead of arrow keys.
    </p>
    <steps>
      <item>
        <p>Enter OCR mode with
          <keyseq><key>Orca Modifier</key><key>R</key></keyseq>.</p>
      </item>
      <item>
        <p>Navigate to the start of the text you want to copy.</p>
      </item>
      <item>
        <p>Press <key>KP Decimal</key> to mark the selection anchor at
          the current cursor position. Orca says "Anchor set at
          [word]."</p>
      </item>
      <item>
        <p>Navigate to the end of the text you want to copy while
          holding <key>Shift</key>. For example,
          <keyseq><key>Shift</key><key>KP 6</key></keyseq> extends the
          selection by one word, <keyseq><key>Shift</key><key>KP 2</key></keyseq>
          by one line, <keyseq><key>Shift</key><key>KP 3</key></keyseq>
          by one character.</p>
      </item>
      <item>
        <p>Press <key>KP Add</key> to copy the selection to the system
          clipboard. Orca says "Copied selection: [preview]." Paste the
          text anywhere with the usual
          <keyseq><key>Ctrl</key><key>V</key></keyseq>.</p>
      </item>
    </steps>
    <p>
      If you only need to copy the current line and have not set an
      anchor, just press <key>KP Add</key> directly — it falls back to
      copying the current line when no selection is active.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="click_workflow">
    <title>Clicking on Things in Inaccessible Applications</title>
    <p>
      Once you have navigated to a word that you want to click, press
      <key>KP Divide</key> (or <key>KP Enter</key>) for a left-click, or
      <key>KP Multiply</key> for a right-click. The click is sent to the
      original source window at the screen position of that word. Because
      the OCR buffer is purely virtual and has no on-screen widget, the
      click reaches the underlying application directly.
    </p>
    <p>
      OCR mode stays active after a click, so you can navigate to another
      word and click again without re-running recognition.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="limits">
    <title>Limitations</title>
    <list>
      <item>
        <p>Recognition quality depends on Tesseract and on the rendered
          text. Small, antialiased, or non-Latin scripts may give
          incorrect results. Confidence-filtered words below the quality
          threshold are silently dropped.</p>
      </item>
      <item>
        <p>OCR recognizes a snapshot of the window's pixels at the moment
          you press the keybinding. If the window content changes
          afterward, the buffer becomes stale. Re-press
          <keyseq><key>Orca Modifier</key><key>R</key></keyseq> to
          re-recognize.</p>
      </item>
      <item>
        <p>Capture works under X11 and under real Wayland. On X11,
          Orca uses an in-process GDK call. On Wayland, Orca uses
          the <cmd>xdg-desktop-portal</cmd> Screenshot service, which
          may prompt for permission the first time you press
          <keyseq><key>Orca Modifier</key><key>R</key></keyseq> in a
          session. Click <gui>Allow</gui>; subsequent OCR calls
          within the same session are typically granted
          automatically.</p>
      </item>
      <item>
        <p>OCR mode temporarily takes over the NumPad keys that are
          normally bound to flat-review commands. The flat-review
          bindings are restored when you exit OCR mode.</p>
      </item>
    </list>
  </section>
</page>
